{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"05efe359-7567-472d-ae1c-20db1636697f","content":"The migration is straightforward. In your project file (or `Directory.Build.props`), simply **remove** (or set to `false`) the `UseVSTest` property:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Key things to know:**\n\n1. **`MSTest.Sdk` ≥ 3.4** defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, so removing `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` is the only required change.\n2. **Running tests** — use `dotnet test` as before, but you can also run the test executable directly (`./MyTests.exe`).\n3. **CLI differences** — filter syntax changes slightly (e.g., `--filter` → `--filter`/`--treenode-filter`). Check `dotnet test --help` for the new options.\n4. **CI/IDE** — Visual Studio 2022 17.10+ and `dotnet test` support the new platform natively. If you use `.runsettings`, they still work but some adapter-specific settings may need review.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4c36f93f-c541-4e0d-b50e-b313e7022052","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory appears to be empty and doesn't contain any relevant project files. This is a general knowledge question about MSTest migration. Let me answer based on my knowledge.\n\nWith MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0 and `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>`, the user is explicitly opting into the legacy VSTest runner. To switch to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, they need to make a simple change.","outputTokens":432,"requestId":"CFE3:1605AB:607E7E2:6BB033A:69EC0ECE"},"id":"aba905f1-6e56-4add-b6a3-8c33ac2b4f66","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:46:17.167Z","parentId":"7ae3d836-bfd9-41e9-a033-6835502233ad"}
